Instagram Followers Analysis

Marina GÃ³mez Rey

Introduction

In the age of social media, understanding the dynamics of online interactions has become increasingly important. One aspect that intrigues many is how to become more popular in the platform and gain followers. For that reason, in this study, this is going to be studied by examining how the number of followers is related to two key factors: the number of accounts a user follows and the number of close friends they have. Particularly, this is studied on Instagram, which has the close Friends facility available. With it, only the selected people are able to see some posts of the user.

Data collection

In order to make this project possible I created a Google forms with this link, in which three questions were asked:

  • How many followers do you have?
  • How many people do you follow?
  • How many people do you have in close friends?

Link to the form: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScuJE_SDkGRMfI21tcmbEOE8-tAHEVNpdmwu7pzh-nJe8Bmkg/viewform?usp=sf_link

Form Picture

The form was shared among friends, who kindly responded to it. The data from these responses were collected into a CSV file for analysis. This data provides a snapshot of social interactions on Instagram among a specific group of users, which will be analyzed to identify patterns and relationships.

Link to the form

As the variable that we are going to study is Followers, and the distribution is not very clear, letâs make a non-specific number of components clustering to see how it is working.

Clustering of the target variable

As a non-specific approach is going to be followed, the prior will be uniform, with a kmax of 30. Also, the MCMC iterations aare defined and the algorithm is called. Then we obtain the

library(mixAK)

Bayesian models

MCMC

In order to solve this problem, as the variable to study is numeric continuous, I will use regression. The model will have the following variable as the one to study and the number of iterations is also defined.

Study the parameters

# Extract coefficients from the Bayesian model
beta <- bayes[, 1:3]  # Exclude the intercept (if present) from the coefficients
sigma2 <- bayes[, 4]

# Calculate the mean coefficients
mean.beta <- apply(beta, 2, mean)
mean.beta
##   (Intercept) Close.Friends     Following 
##    22.8823777     3.7882839     0.5938838
mean(sigma2)
## [1] 44964.73
apply(beta, 2, median)
##   (Intercept) Close.Friends     Following 
##    22.5135241     3.7848765     0.5939582
median(sigma2)
## [1] 43741.93
apply(beta, 2, quantile, c(0.025, 0.975))
##       (Intercept) Close.Friends Following
## 2.5%    -95.07993      1.613590 0.4128378
## 97.5%   143.36478      5.975404 0.7740405

*Note that the values may have changed slightly as different iterations may give different results.

With that confidence intervals we can learn very important and insightful information. It means that each new close friend will mean that the user will gain from 1.844485 to 6.731641 followers (approximately 4.2845346 as the mean says), and each following from 0.3658194 and 0.7556903 (approximately 0.5636976). This means that both affect positively, and a user will benefit from more followers when performing the previous actions.

Also, with this information we can predict how many followers a user will have based on specific values of close friends and following. Letâs perform an example of a user that has 30 close friends and 500 following.

x.new = c(1, 30, 500)
x.new%*%apply(beta,2,mean)
##          [,1]
## [1,] 433.4728
# Confidence interval
quantile(x.new%*%t(beta),probs=c(0.025,0.975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 374.8664 492.6797
# Predictive interval
y.pred=rnorm(dim(beta)[1],x.new%*%t(beta),sqrt(sigma2))
quantile(y.pred,probs=c(0.025,0.975))
##      2.5%     97.5% 
##  13.88693 853.93236

Approximately, this user will have 433 followers. In order to make more predictions and see how the model works, we can predict all the values from the test set and plot them with the originals to see how well it is behaving.

Evaluate with the test set

# Prepare predictor variables for the test set
n <- dim(data_test)[1]
X <- cbind(rep(1, n), data_test$Close.Friends, data_test$Following)  

# Predict the response variable
predicted <- X %*% mean.beta

# Plot actual vs. predicted values
plot(data_test$Followers, predicted)
abline(0, 1, col = "red")

Seeing that the majority of the values are very close to the red line, it can be seen that the model makes a good prediction on the number of followers of the user.

R2OpenBugs

The same model that was computed using MCMC is now going to be computed in Open Bugs. Following a regression, the normal distribution is used, so we need mu and phi as parameters within the distribution, and mu will depend then on beta and the variables to study.

Also, as in the other model the number of followers of a person with 30 close friends and 500 following, it will also be computed here.

library(R2OpenBUGS)

model <- function(){
  for (i in 1:N) {
    Followers[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], phi)
    mu[i] <- beta0 + beta1 * Close.Friends[i] + beta2 * Following[i]
  }
  
  # Priors
  beta0 ~ dnorm(0.0, 1.0E-6)
  beta1 ~ dnorm(0.0, 1.0E-6)
  beta2 ~ dnorm(0.0, 1.0E-6)
  phi ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  sigma2 <- 1 / phi
  
  followers.new ~ dnorm(mu.new, phi)
  mu.new <- beta0 + beta1 * close.friends.new + beta2 * following.new
}

N <- length(data_train$Followers)
data <- list(N = N,
             Followers = data_train$Followers,
             Close.Friends = data_train$Close.Friends,
             Following = data_train$Following,
             close.friends.new = 30,
             following.new = 500
)


inits <- function() {list(beta0 = 0, beta1 = 0, beta2 = 0, phi = 0.5, followers.new = 250)}

# Run the model
output <- bugs(data = data, inits = inits,
               parameters.to.save = c("beta0", "beta1", "beta2", "sigma2", "mu.new", "followers.new"), model.file = model,
               n.chains = 1, n.iter = 11000, n.burnin = 1000)

## pD = 4.0 and DIC = 788.9
## DIC is an estimate of expected predictive error (lower deviance is better).

The output seems similar to the one obtained previously on the other model. The confidence intervals almost coincide, as well as the values of the mean and the standard deviation, what shows that the models are computed correctly, and the conclusions are also correct.

Letâs check that there is no autocorrelation and it converges.

Conclusions

Letâs make a summary of all the techniques applied: data preprocessing where iIrrelevant columns were removed, and outliers were handled to ensure data quality, relationships between the variables where scatter plots revealed a linear relationship between followers and the number of accounts followed, and between followers and close friends, analysis of the distribution that showed right-skewedness, brief frequentist analysis in which linear regression confirmed that both close friends and following are significant predictors of followers and the bayesian analysis using both MCMC and OpenBugs that supported the frequentist results, providing credible intervals that further confirmed the significance of both predictors. Also, the results were checked with a test set and were closely related, so the results are robust.

The main insights that have been obtained is that both the number of close friends and following users is relevant and influence in a positive way the number of followers, so if any user wants to grow in that app, a good practice can be to enlarge this two aspects.

In order to make a further analysis and explore other variables, some other instagram features could be included such as the number of posts, if the account is public or private (categorical) or the amount of time a day the user passes on the app. Also, more data would provide better results that would make more precise predictions.
